<section xml:id="Linear_Independence">
  <title>Linear Independence</title>
  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A subset <m>\mathbb{S} = \{ \mathbf{P}_1,\mathbf{P}_2,\ldots,\mathbf{P}_n\}</m> of a linear space <m>\mathbb{L}</m> is
        <term>linearly independent</term>
        if every point <m>\mathbf{Q}</m> in
        <m>span\mathbb{S}</m> can be written in only one way as a linear combination using elements of <m>\mathbb{S}</m>.
        More specifically, for any real numbers
        <m>a_1,a_2,\ldots,a_n</m> and <m>b_1,b_2,\ldots,b_n</m>:
        <me>
          a_1\mathbf{P}_1 + a_2\mathbf{P}_2 +\cdots+a_n\mathbf{P}_n = b_1\mathbf{P}_1 + b_2\mathbf{P}_2 +\cdots+ b_n\mathbf{P}_n  \Longrightarrow a_1=b_1,\ldots a_n=b_n
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        A subset <m>\mathbb{S}</m> is <term>linearly dependent</term>
        if <m>\mathbb{S}</m> is not linearly independent.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Show how to write the point
        <m>\ot{a}{b}{c}</m> as a linear combination of the points in <m>\mathbb{S} = \{ \ot{1}{2}{0},\ot{1}{0}{0},\ot{1}{1}{0} \}</m>.
        Is the set <m>\mathbb{S}</m> linearly independent?
        If it is not,
        show how some point can be written in more than one way as a linear combination of the elements of <m>\mathbb{S}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        What is the additive identity element in the linear space<nbsp/><m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>? ...in the linear space
        <m>\mathbb{P}</m>? ..in the linear space C[0,1]?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Describe the steps needed to prove:
        <me>
          (A \Longrightarrow B) \Longleftrightarrow (C \Longrightarrow D)
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <theorem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>\mathbb{S} = \{ \mathbf{P}_1 , \mathbf{P}_2 ,\ldots, \mathbf{P}_n \}</m> be a subset of linear space <m>\mathbb{L}</m>.
        Then the set <m>\mathbb{S}</m> is linearly independent if and only if for all real numbers <m>c_1,c_2,\ldots,c_n</m>,
        <m>c_1\mathbf{P}_1 + c_2\mathbf{P}_2 +\cdots+c_n\mathbf{P}_n = \mathbf{0}</m> implies all of the coefficients <m>c_i</m> are zero.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>
  <aside>
    <p>
      The most difficult part of this proof is setting it up correctly.
      It is also important that student are clear that
      <m>A \Rightarrow B</m> being true does not mean <m>A</m> must be true.
    </p>
  </aside>
</section>